Random Recipe is a Canadian musical group founded in 2007 in Montreal, Quebec, Canada. The band is comprised of members Frannie Holder (vocals/guitar), Fabrizia Difruscia (rap/beatbox), Vincent Legault (guitar/keys), and Liu-Kong Ha (percussion/keys).<ref>{{cite web|last=CBC Music|title=Random Recipe|url=http://music.cbc.ca/#/artists/Random-Recipe|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>.  Although the band performs and records primarily in English, many of their songs contain French, Spanish and Italian lyrics.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nelischer|first=Claire|title=All the right stuff Random Recipe is gaining notoriety playing impromptu shows at poutineries and pizzerias|url=http://queensjournal.ca/story/2011-02-03/arts/all-right-stuff/?flavour=mobile|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=The Queen's Journal, Queen's University|date=3 February 2011}}</ref> In 2008, they were hailed by Spin Magazine as one of the top 5 up-and-coming Montreal bands.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rabinovitch|first=Simona|title=SPIN.com's Top 5 Up-and-Coming Montreal Bands|url=http://www.spin.com/articles/spincoms-top-5-and-coming-montreal-bands/|work=Spin Magazine|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>
== History ==

Frannie and Fab met in 2005 whilst both were university students, studying political science at McGill University and translation at Concordia University, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|last=Cromp|first=MJ|title=Random Recipe - Meet Colorful Frannie Holder|url=http://www.ixdaily.com/the-buzz/76eb912fee7ea06e0188fee4ba82d40a04d5389d|work=IX Daily|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>   Their first public performances were free-of-charge and spontaneous, including busking in parks, taxis, and on the Montreal metro, and they continue to put on impromptu shows at poutineries and pizzerias.<ref>{{cite news|last=Nelischer|first=Claire|title=All the right stuff Random Recipe is gaining notoriety playing impromptu shows at poutineries and pizzerias|url=http://queensjournal.ca/story/2011-02-03/arts/all-right-stuff/?flavour=mobile|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=The Queen's Journal, Queen's University|date=3 February 2011}}</ref>  Their sound has been described as ecclectic yet accessible; a mix between Cocorosie and the Beastie Boys.  <ref>{{cite news|last=Therien|first=Valerie|title=Serendipitous sounds: Montreal<U+2019>s Random Recipe|url=http://www.mcgilldaily.com/2008/03/serendipitous_sounds_montreals_random_recipe/|accessdate=20 February 2014|newspaper=The McGill Daily|date=20 March 2008}}</ref> Vincent Legault and Liu-Kong Ha (both classically trained musicians, having studied percussion and guitar jazz at McGill University and the Conservatoire de musique du Qu<U+00E9>bec <U+00E0> Montr<U+00E9>al)<ref>{{cite web|last=Cromp|first=MJ|title=Random Recipe - Meet Colorful Frannie Holder|url=http://www.ixdaily.com/the-buzz/76eb912fee7ea06e0188fee4ba82d40a04d5389d|work=IX Daily|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> later joined the band, rounding out their sound to include instruments as diverse as the xylophone, melodica, ombichord, steel drums, and kazoo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Random Recipe|url=http://www.randomrecipe.ca/en/bio-press/|work=Random Recipe|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>   In February of 2014, the band announced the addition of a 5th member, Florent Legault, as well as revealing that Frannie and Fab were once romantically linked but have since ended their relationship, remaining close friends.<ref>{{cite web|last=Blitz|first=Merissa|title=Random Recipe: The Beautiful Connection|url=http://www.sogutsy.com/2014/02/19/random-recipe-the-beautiful-connection/|work=So Gutsy|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>
== Touring ==

The quartet have toured throughout Quebec and the rest of Canada, as well as in the United States, France, Belgium, and Iceland.  They have also performed several times at the prestigious Montreal International Jazz Festival and the Festival d'<U+00E9>t<U+00E9> de Qu<U+00E9>bec (2010 and 2011), as well as at M for Montreal (2010 and 2011), and the Halifax Pop Explosion (2010).<ref>{{cite web|title=Shows|url=http://www.randomrecipe.ca/en/shows/|work=Random Recipe|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>  On Parliament Hill in Ottawa in July 2011, Random Recipe participated in the Canada Day Celebrations, performing to an audience that included William and Kate, the Duke and Duchess of Cambridge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada<U+2019>s Top Talent to Headline Canada Day on Parliament Hill|url=http://www.pch.gc.ca/eng/1307637039872/1307637245272|work=Government of Canada, Department of Canadian Heritage|publisher=Government of Canada|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>  In 2011 they played at the SXSW festival in Austin, Texas, and will return in March 2014 to play the SXSW festival once more.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shows|url=http://www.randomrecipe.ca/en/shows/|work=Random Recipe|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref>
== Accomplishments ==

Random Recipe has also been awarded several prizes for their performances, including the 2011 Miroir for the Best Canadian Artist Prize and RIDEAU's 2011 <U+00C9>toiles Galaxie prize.  Following the release of Fold It! Mold It! in September of 2010 in Canada through Bonsound and in January of 2012 in France via Chapter Two Records, the band was nominated in three categories at the 2011 ADISQ (Album of the year - Anglophone, Quebec artist of the year - Other languages, and Album artwork of the year). Since then, Random Recipe has multiplied collaborations with widely known artists such as Pierre Lapointe, DJ Champion and J<U+00E9>r<U+00F4>me Mini<U+00E8>re.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Random Recipe|url=http://www.randomrecipe.ca/en/bio-press/|work=Random Recipe|accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> In 2009 they received the award for best new group by the Montreal International Music Initiative (MIMI).<ref>{{cite web|title=Here Are Your MIMI Winners|url=http://www.chartattack.com/news/2009/02/06/here-are-your-mimi-winners/|work=Chart Attack}}</ref>
